eshmun.gui.kripke.utils.graphphysics

Class GraphPhysics

  • java.lang.Object
    • eshmun.gui.kripke.utils.graphphysics.GraphPhysics

  • public class GraphPhysics
extends java.lang.Object
    Graph Physics, Automatically space out and position a graph in a nice way.

    This is done by considering the graph to be a physical systems, in which nodes are charged particles and edges are connecting cables or springs.

    The simulation is carried out for a determined amount of iterations. It utilizes Coloumb's law and Hook's law.

    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    George E. Zakhour, Mohammad Ali Beydoun, Kinan Dak Al Bab

      • calculateIterations

        private int calculateIterations(int nodeCount,
                                int edgeCount)
        Computes the number of iterations that would be appropriate for the simulation to reach an adequate state.

        This is done through the given equation: f(x, y) = 1000 + 500log(1 + 1000x)log(1 + 1000y)
        Where x, y are the number of nodes, edges respectively.

        Parameters:
        nodeCount - The number of nodes in the graph
        edgeCount - The number of edges in the graph
        Returns:
        the number of iterations required.

      • transform

        private java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,Node> transform(java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,Node> nodes,
                                                           java.util.List<Edge> edges,
                                                           int iterations)
        Simulates the graph as a physical system of repulsive and attraction force (by the use of Coulomb's and Hooke's laws).
        Parameters:
        nodes - The nodes in the graph mapped by their name (unique), the nodes will be modified in place with the new position.
        edges - List of edges in the graph
        iterations - the maximum number of iterations to run.
        Returns:
        the same mapping with positions updated.
